comments:
First off, the videos were informative, if not somewhat simplistic, but all were way out of date (270+ mass shootings in the US so far this year, and it's only June, while one video from 2015 showed 111 mass shootings in the US over a four year period and thought that was terrible).  Basically the gun problem has gotten way worse since these videos were released.
"A well regulated Militia, being necessary to the security of a free State, the right of the people to keep and bear Arms, shall not be infringed."  The Second Amendment as it interpreted today as giving complete license for every paranoid nutjob to own a firearm has absolutely nothing to do with its original intent.  How its name and not its words or meaning came to be the mantra of an obsessed and insecure minority, and have come to reek such havoc on this country is a scam, a swindle and somewhat of a mystery to those who are literate and able to understand and properly interpret a written statement.  In other words- where the hell is the well regulated militia which should be associated with every gun owner?
Oh, something I thought of years ago, even before Chris Rock joked about it.  "Guns don't kill people, bullets do."  How about a very steep bullet tax?  And every bullet needs to be engraved with a serial number and registered.  How about a $200 per bullet tax, and a $10,000 fine for possession of each bullet without a serial number engraved on it or improperly registered.  I am sure that policy would put a significant dent in gun mayhem.  Let them have all the guns they want.  Just make the bullets very expensive and very scarce.
Lastly- General questions are problematic.  Do I trust mainstream media outlets?  A question like this puts NBC News on the same level as Fox News.  NBC News has integrity, Fox has none.  I am sorry, a network like Fox that depends on lies to maintain its audience has no credibility, but one might think that it is considered a mainstream news source, at least by some.  For questions like "do you trust ...politicians?" (for example, or news sources, etc.) there must be specificity (Trump?  McConnell?  Biden?  Harris? , not the generic "politician".  Or CNN?  New York Times?  OAN?  NewsMax?, not the generic "news source".  Asking questions with broad generalities leads to confusion and doers not yield any meaningful results.  Questions need specificity.
Good luck with your project.
